25,0.03817835,-0.05220423,0.09505326,0.00271849,0.03107090,0.06716861,-0.02597554,0.01152371,-0.01014114,0.07721248,-0.06746826,-0.00747436,-0.07031198,0.04339623,-0.01485599,-0.00537884,-0.01970432,-0.01037464,-0.02848169,-0.02403912,-0.01814092,-0.02638014,-0.04910299,-0.00923526,-0.03768090,-0.07809408,0.01373839,-0.01933864,-0.08899647,-0.03568574,-0.01891020,0.04127237,-0.02775515,0.01858838,0.00081500,-0.02051454,0.03769634,0.02775084,0.00339151,0.07166932,0.02399120,0.01207269]',E'Register\n\nYour routes, your utilities, and so on are all plugins. To add a new plugin,\nwhatever its functionality may be, in Fastify you have a nice and unique API:\n[`register`](../Reference/Plugins.md).\n```js\nfastify.register(\n  require(''./my-plugin''),\n  { options }\n)\n```\n`register` creates a new Fastify context, which means that if you perform any\nchanges on the Fastify instance, those changes will not be reflected in the\ncontext''s ancestors. In other words, encapsulation!','{"source": "fastify", "version": "5", "language": "javascript", "title": "The hitchhiker''s guide to plugins", "section_title": "Plugins-Guide", "url": "https://github.com/fastify/fastify/blob/main/docs/Guides/Plugins-Guide.md", "topics": "fastify,node,http,Plugins,Guide", "categories": "web,javascript,rest"}');
