0.18437043,0.03670053,-0.01106336,0.02470509,0.00420648,0.01020939,0.00937367,-0.00632613,0.00351869,0.00179589,0.03286219,-0.09531692,0.00725733,-0.06509502,0.02477871,0.06960361,0.02364316,-0.01777196,0.06489269,-0.03347024,-0.01621415,-0.01205081,-0.01144853,-0.04100416,0.00277129,-0.05680308,-0.03320410,0.00405291,-0.00902787,-0.06390559,-0.03378640,-0.04880488,0.02301552,-0.04353884,0.01136907,0.04908860,-0.01449523,0.04534192,0.06690657,-0.04197358,0.04376494,0.02608426,0.01774105]',E'How to handle encapsulation and distribution\n\nAs we mentioned earlier, Fastify starts loading its plugins __after__\n`.listen()`, `.inject()` or `.ready()` are called and as such, __after__ they\nhave been declared. This means that, even though the plugin may inject variables\nto the external Fastify instance via [`decorate`](../Reference/Decorators.md),\nthe decorated variables will not be accessible before calling `.listen()`,\n`.inject()`, or `.ready()`.','{"source": "fastify", "version": "5", "language": "javascript", "title": "The hitchhiker''s guide to plugins", "section_title": "Plugins-Guide", "url": "https://github.com/fastify/fastify/blob/main/docs/Guides/Plugins-Guide.md", "topics": "fastify,node,http,Plugins,Guide", "categories": "web,javascript,rest"}');
