12,0.04259097,0.17167197,0.04325394,-0.07003351,0.06941181,0.01801923,-0.00814774,0.10703392,-0.01607492,0.01239362,0.02050688,0.08602692,0.03069174,-0.00381939,-0.07740138,-0.01823140,-0.01090547,-0.03604637,-0.06038769,0.02344476,-0.00494905,0.02766725,-0.02270227,0.05413223,-0.04871155,-0.05277967,-0.08254263,-0.02539603,-0.00187193,-0.00453010,-0.08467574,-0.02956605,-0.01141116,0.02444578,-0.00465524,0.03894721,0.07960176,-0.05532080,0.01925073,-0.01961806,0.03485268,0.07590885,0.04791407,-0.03595821]',E'Error Handling\n\nWhen schema validation fails for a request, Fastify will automatically return a\nstatus 400 response including the result from the validator in the payload. For\nexample, if the following schema is used for a route:\n\n```js\nconst schema = {\n  body: {\n    type: ''object'',\n    properties: {\n      name: { type: ''string'' }\n    },\n    required: [''name'']\n  }\n}\n```\n\nIf the request fails to satisfy the schema, the route will return a response\nwith the following payload:','{"source": "fastify", "version": "5", "language": "javascript", "title": "Validation And Serialization", "section_title": "Validation-and-Serialization", "url": "https://github.com/fastify/fastify/blob/main/docs/Reference/Validation-and-Serialization.md", "topics": "fastify,node,http,Validation,and,Serialization", "categories": "web,javascript,rest"}');
